        {
          "$type": "text",
          "text": "Lee, I'm really glad you brought this up — two weeks of sharp knee pain is absolutely worth taking seriously, and it makes sense you're looking for answers.\n\nI have to be straight with you here: diagnosing what's causing your knee pain is genuinely outside my lane as a coach. Sharp pain that's lasted two weeks, especially on stairs, needs a proper assessment from a physiotherapist or sports medicine doctor — someone who can actually examine the joint, rule out anything structural, and give you a real answer. That's not me hedging; it's just the honest truth about where coaching ends and medicine begins.\n\nOn the ibuprofen question specifically — I'd hold off on taking it *before* runs. That's a conversation to have with your doctor or physio, not something I can safely advise on.\n\n**What I can tell you from a coaching standpoint:** continuing to run through sharp, persistent pain — even shortened runs — carries real risk of turning a manageable issue into a longer setback. And given your IT band history, your knee deserves extra attention, not a wait-and-see approach.\n\n---\n\nHere's what I'd suggest as a clear next step: **get in to see a physio or sports medicine doc as soon as you can** — ideally this week. The sooner you have a diagnosis, the sooner we can build a smart path forward together.\n\nOnce you have medical clearance and some guidance on what's going on, I'm absolutely ready to adjust your plan. You've got until July 11th, and there's real room to work with here — this doesn't have to derail your half marathon goal.\n\nCan I ask — do you have access to a physio or sports medicine provider you could reach out to?"
        }
      ],
      "messageId": "msg_018z7WTycExtrnBGvGfanugs"
    }
  ],
